prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: RM at band 7
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Polarization observations of 5 bright AGN at band 7 to determine if Rotation Measures from 10^8 to 10^9 rad/m^2 are present. This will indicate magnetized regions near the jet base and accretion disk with ~10 G magnetic fields.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
We are using the standards TDM polarization correlation setup.

THEY ARE SEPARATED BY MORE THA 10 DEG, HENCE, THE PRESENT OT WANTS A SEPARATE SCIENCE GOAL AND WOULD CALIBRATED EACH OF THE INDEPENDENTLY, EVEN THOUGH THE ONE CALIBRATOR 3C279 IS SUITABLE FOR ALL. BUT THIS WAS NECESSARY FOR THE PROPOSAL TO 'PASS'. IF ACDEPTED, WE WILL MAKE THE APPROPRIATE CHANGES.

We chose the C36-4 configuration at band 7 in order to have 0.2" resolution. There is very little source extended emission. Higher resolution is possible (C36-5,6), but the source selection depends on the LST available, and C36-4 is the best available in 2015.

This SNR is associated with the entire 7.5 GHz bandwidth. The analysis we will do will use the narrow band channels (31 MHz) with a much lower SNR. In addition, it is the polarized emission that will be maily analyzed, and it is about 2% for these sources. Hence, the SNR per channel for the polarization is about 44000 / sqrt(256) / 50 = 600. This is more than enough, but we are observing each source three times in order to determine the D-term stability in order to determine small RM wiggles.

This is complicated. See proposal.
We have selected only the D-term calibrator 3c279. We also want observations of 3c286 to confirm the absolute position angle of the polarization. The problem of the sources extended over a large area (spread of target positions too large) is not relevant for this type of experiment, and we have cheated by moving the three targets together. This will be fixed in phase 2.
This was addressed in the RMS/SNR discussion above.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose observing three active galactic nuclei (AGN) with ALMA between 336 and 351 GHz in full polarization mode to search for extremely high Faraday depths from the measurement of their rotation measures, RM. The existence of such dense magnetized media is expected near the super-massive black hole and inner jet collimation regions, and recent observations of the RM of 1830-211 suggest the presence of magnetic fields up to 10 Gauss. With the demonstrated accuracy of the degree of polarization to 0.3% and polarization angle of 1.0 deg, the rotation measures from the magnetized media with values between 10^{8} to 10^{9} rad/m^2 can be detected from small polarization angle wiggles over the observed frequency range. The AGN selected are those that are strong and compact, with a history of variability and a probable dense nuclear region. The major goal of this proposal is to study properties of the jet media: magnetic field strength weighted by particle density in regions close to the SMBH and jet origin. They are directly related to and will constrain the jet launching models.
